WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.120
I’m Danny, and I’ll be your instructor for this case study.

2
00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:04.120


3
00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:04.120


4
00:00:04.120 --> 00:00:08.920
A case study is an examination of a particular real-world problem.

5
00:00:08.920 --> 00:00:14.880
Doing a case study helps you strengthen your skills by practicing what you have learned in other courses.

6
00:00:14.880 --> 00:00:20.880
So, the focus is on combining your skills to bring solutions to a real-world problem.

7
00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:20.880


8
00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:20.880


9
00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:25.760
For this case study, you might need concepts from these courses.

10
00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:25.760


11
00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:25.800


12
00:00:25.800 --> 00:00:30.880
Before analyzing our business problem, it is important to clearly understand the steps involved.

13
00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:30.880


14
00:00:30.880 --> 00:00:31.440


15
00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:36.040
First, start by making sure the data needed is present and clean.

16
00:00:36.040 --> 00:00:43.760
For example, structuring the data, correcting typing mistakes, removing duplicate values, and other possible errors.

17
00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:43.760


18
00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:43.800


19
00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:46.040
Then, explore your data.

20
00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:49.360
It can help you get familiar with the information, think of possible

21
00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:53.480
calculations, and identify potential side problems and ways to solve them.

22
00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:54.600


23
00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:54.600


24
00:00:54.600 --> 00:00:58.360
The following step is to analyze and visualize the data.

25
00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:04.080
Here you focus on the problem and try multiple ways to solve it, to obtain the best possible result.

26
00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:04.080


27
00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:04.840


28
00:01:04.840 --> 00:01:09.160
The last step is to prepare a report where you can show the most important results

29
00:01:09.160 --> 00:01:13.960
from your analysis in a clear way with one or more dashboards and communicate insights.

30
00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:14.920


31
00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:14.920


32
00:01:14.920 --> 00:01:21.800
In this case study, you will use a fictitious dataset from a company called WarmeHands Incorporated.

33
00:01:21.800 --> 00:01:26.480
You are hired as a consultant to analyze the inventory data and give some

34
00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:32.400
insights into which would be the best items for renewing or increasing inventory.

35
00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:32.400


36
00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:32.400


37
00:01:32.400 --> 00:01:34.920
What is an inventory analysis?

38
00:01:34.920 --> 00:01:40.680
Inventory analysis is a management technique that can help you optimize inventory control.

39
00:01:40.680 --> 00:01:48.160
For instance, it can help you reduce storage expenses, item costs, and unused goods and to increase profit.

40
00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:53.640
There are many ways to do inventory analysis, but for this case study a basic approach will be used.

41
00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:53.640


42
00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:53.640


43
00:01:53.640 --> 00:01:58.560
Starting with a basic approach, you will use some important calculations and

44
00:01:58.560 --> 00:02:04.320
methods for inventory analysis that will be shown gradually throughout the course.

45
00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:12.240
In this first part, you will use revenue, cost of goods sold, and profit calculations.

46
00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:12.240


47
00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:12.240


48
00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:17.440
Revenue is the amount of money a company receives in exchange for its goods and services.

49
00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:17.440


50
00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:23.440
The simplest way companies calculate revenue is by multiplying the total number of units sold by their selling price.

51
00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:23.440


52
00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:23.440


53
00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:28.200
Cost of goods sold, or COGS, refers to the cost of producing

54
00:02:28.200 --> 00:02:32.200
or acquiring products that a company sells in a determined period.

55
00:02:32.200 --> 00:02:36.880
It only accounts for production costs such as raw materials, labor, and

56
00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:41.680
manufacturing overhead, excluding the cost of selling the product and transportation.

57
00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:41.680


58
00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:42.600


59
00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:47.720
For example, the COGS of a wooden chair for a traditional wooden chair-making company

60
00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:54.240
would be the price of wood, glue, finishers, and labor, but not the distribution of the product.

61
00:02:54.240 --> 00:02:58.440
So, our COGS for a wooden chair would be the price of wood plus the

62
00:02:58.440 --> 00:03:03.520
price of glue plus the price of wood finishers plus the price of labor.

63
00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:03.520


64
00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:03.520


65
00:03:03.520 --> 00:03:11.280
The gross profit is the amount resulting after subtracting costs associated with making or acquiring products.

66
00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:14.640
It is calculated by subtracting COGS from total revenue.

67
00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:14.640


68
00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:14.640


69
00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:20.880
The WarmeHands dataset contains six tables where you will find information on the ID code of

70
00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:28.600
the items (written also as "SKU" or "SKU-ID"), their description, initial stock quantities,

71
00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:34.920
individual orders with their respective quantities and dates, order country of precedence, and price.

72
00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:34.920


73
00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:37.800
It is your job to make the best use of this information.

74
00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:37.800


75
00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:37.800


76
00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:43.560
It's time to check your understanding of the steps needed in the analysis development process.

77
00:03:43.560 --> 00:03:46.680
Let's practice!

